40|$|Abstract—The {{design of}} {{automated}} online security and intru-sion tolerance solutions for computer systems and networks is a theoretically achievable objective. However, {{after two decades}} of research, this objective has still not yet successfully passed the practicality test to become widely adopted. We believe that the main reason behind this gap lies in the misleading definition of autonomous security that precludes human intervention in trying to achieve unrealistic level of full automation. In this position paper, we discuss a novel research direction to address this challenge through a coherent integration of human intelligence. In particular, we identify the key questions to be answered in order to enable human intelligence to be leveraged in a seamless manner and without requiring explicit heavy human involvements. We illustrate our discussion through the preliminary design of a semi-automated <b>intrusion</b> <b>detection</b> <b>and</b> <b>response</b> system that incorporates reasonable human input to achieve higher levels of intrusion tolerance efficiency. Keywords-Online <b>intrusion</b> <b>detection</b> <b>and</b> <b>response,</b> collabo-rative filtering, system security visualization. I...|$|E
40|$|Modern {{intrusions}} {{are often}} across {{sites that are}} not under centralized control. Most of the successful intruders launch attacks by breaking into a chain of systems to hide their identity. That's why information sharing among such systems is vital if such attacks are to be identi ed, analyzed later and their source correctly traced back. Also data sharing and coordination is required to identify and respond to attacks in progress which are usually launched from unrelated domains, e. g., Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks. Although system administrators share information among themselves there hasn't been much work done {{in the area of}} automated cooperative ID&R (<b>Intrusion</b> <b>Detection</b> <b>and</b> <b>Response).</b> One of the primary factors behind this is that no frameworks exist for domains without a central administration to safely and conveniently share data that may be used to track distributed intrusions and respond to them. In this project we are suggesting such a framework to support cooperative <b>intrusion</b> <b>detection</b> <b>and</b> <b>response</b> within a domain as well as across distributed domains. Acknowledgement...|$|E
